<subSubSection id="9983A9D91B08FFC4FF16F596FE25F499" pageId="22" pageNumber="533" type="description">
<paragraph id="D126FA521B08FFC4FF16F596FE25F499" blockId="22.[130,1335,2505,3199]" pageId="22" pageNumber="533">
<emphasis id="E3ED26401B08FFC4FF16F596FE16F5D4" bold="true" box="[130,390,2535,2568]" pageId="22" pageNumber="533">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 183 mm, tail 77 mm, hindfoot 34 mm (all measurements from the adult female holotype). No specific data are available for body weight. The Brown Tuco-tuco is medium-sized. It is uniform drab brown above without dark spots, and under parts are pale and buffy. Tail is brown above and whitish below. Skull is rather narrow, and braincase lacks strong ridges. Zygomatic arches are not widely expanded and have medially ascending process placed posteriorly, which results in orbits larger than temporal fossa. Nasals are long and nearly parallel-sided. Bullae are long and narrow, quite different from the Mendoza Tucotuco (
<taxonomicName id="169981D11B08FFC4FF4FF759FE39F499" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1869" box="[219,425,2856,2885]" class="Mammalia" family="Ctenomyidae" genus="Ctenomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="22" pageNumber="533" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mendocinus">C. mendocinus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
